issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I have a collection created by a plugin that I would like to not sync to my production deployment. Adding this collection to the list of excluded collections prompts a failed Zod schema validation, since it is only allowing the built in collections in the list.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Either as a seperate config option, or as part of excludeCollections, I would like to be able to add my custom collection to the list of collections not pull/pushed

performed_via_github_app.description: This bot will comment on PRs saying that either a user might need to add a changeset(note that PRs changing things like documentation generally don't need a changeset)or say that the PR is good and already has a changeset. Sometimes, a contributor won't add a changeset to a PR but you might want to merge in the PR without having to wait on them to add it. To address this, this bot adds a link with the filename pre-filled to add a changeset so all you have to do is write the changeset and click commit. When writing the changeset, it should look something like this with the packages that are being released in the YAML front matter with associated semver bump types and the summary of the changes in markdown. ```markdown --- '@changesets/cli': major '@changesets/read': minor --- A very helpful description of the changes ```

issue.body:
## Purpose
Add a new option `add_partial_tags` to handle creation and update of partial tags for major and major.minor.



## Rationale
It will simplify the CI process for project using partial tags, as it will no more require to add scripts to update those after performing a version bump with psr.

## How did you test?
For now, I only did manual testing. I need more time to setup a fully working test environment and investigate the way the tests are written. That's why the PR is opened as draft for now, just so you know that I'm working on the feature and can have a first look at it. I should have some spare time at the end of the month or in january to look at the tests.

- Set `add_partial_tags` to `true` in configuration.
- Run psr --no-op version on a project with partial tags.

issue.title: Attaching a table with multiple names
issue.body:
### Company or project name

_No response_

### Question

We have an issue, that we have introduced some breaking changes to our partition by, order by keys in our clickhouse database. There are loads of services that use our cluster for analytics/data.

We have created newer versions of our tables, with a pattern like this: `<db_name>.<table_name>_v2`. We want to rename the old tables to `<db_name>.<table_name>_v1`, and have something like an alias to `<db_name>.<table_name>_v2` to match to `<db_name>.<table_name>`. Since our environment is evolving, there might be issues with _v2, and we might move to _v3 in future and things like this.

TLDR: we want to have a table name that our clients can use, but we want to have that name aliased to our latest versions of that table. `database.table_vN` should map to `target_database.table_name` that the client uses for queries.

Is this possible in clickhouse as of now?

comment.body:
>Can I use the merge table function infront of a distributed table? Imagine I have distributed tables for each of my table versions.

Yes, you can. Infront (better) and behind. 


And you can do even more complex things.

My production usecase looks like this:
```
                                                                                 --> T_old:MergeTree 
                                                                               /
                                 --> ClusterUS (D:Distributed) -> M: Merge --
                               /                                              \
ClusterALL (D:Distributed) ---                                                  ---> T_new:MergeTree 
                               \
                                ---> ClusterEU (D:Distributed) -> T_new:MergeTree 
```
